        <Abstract>
          <AbstractText>Addison's disease typically results from the autoimmune destruction of the adrenal cortex and requires lifelong replacement with glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids. Main symptoms are non-specific and, therefore, often overlooked or misleading. Patients are frequently not diagnosed until experiencing a life-threatening adrenal crisis. This article highlights the essential clinical characteristics, diagnostic aspects and principles of management of adrenal insufficiency.</AbstractText>
